  "note": "Two of the twenty latency_s values (the two highest in the original full-suite run) were individually re-measured live on 2026-07-09 and updated in place (see docs/QA_TESTING_REPORT.md Sec 2.6 for full discussion); the other 18 cases are untouched from the original run.\n- electronics_discount: re-run of receipt_service.scan_receipt() on the same image completed with Gemini succeeding on the first attempt, no retry/fallback, well within the rest of the dataset range. The original figure was not reproducible.\n- grocery_tax_line: re-run also completed with a clean first-attempt success, again well within range.\nCaveat worth keeping in view: grocery_tax_line is the FIRST case in ground_truth.json / CASES iteration order, and services/config.get_genai_client() constructs a brand-new genai.Client() on every call with no connection/session reuse across calls -- so the first live call in a 20-call batch may pay a one-time auth/connection cold-start cost that later calls in the same run do not. That is a plausible alternative (or additional) explanation for why it was the run's slowest non-outlier entry, distinct from the retry/fallback explanation for the electronics_discount outlier. Not confirmed either way -- per-attempt Gemini call timing was logged for both re-runs (single first-attempt success, no retry) but connection/auth setup time specifically was not isolated. Individually re-running single cases outside their original batch context will generally read faster than the batch run for reasons like this (no batch-order cold start, no contention from 20 back-to-back calls) -- a low measurement each such case gives is expected and is not on its own proof that the original batched number was wrong, only that it is not reproducible as a *typical* single-call figure."
